# Local Gradle build settings ‚Äî copy to local.properties and fill in your values.
# This file is committed to version control as a template.
# local.properties is git-ignored and must NOT be committed.
#
# First-time setup:
#
#   cp local.properties.example local.properties
#   # Edit local.properties and fill in SUPABASE_URL + SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY
#   # (the only two required keys for backend connectivity). Other settings
#   # are optional ‚Äî leave them empty for local-only mode (no analytics, no
#   # subscription, no live backend).
#
# Read by:
#   - shared/build.gradle.kts          ‚Üí SUPABASE_URL, SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY,
#                                          REVENUECAT_API_KEY_ANDROID
#   - androidApp/build.gradle.kts      ‚Üí SENTRY_DSN_ANDROID, POSTHOG_API_KEY,
#                                          POSTHOG_HOST, KEYSTORE_FILE,
#                                          KEYSTORE_PASSWORD, KEY_ALIAS,
#                                          KEY_PASSWORD
#
# These keys are shared with iosApp/local.xcconfig where applicable (Supabase
# URL + Publishable Key are the same on both platforms; Sentry and PostHog
# have iOS-specific equivalents ‚Äî see iosApp/local.xcconfig.example).
#
# CI fallback: each key is also read from the matching shell environment
# variable when local.properties is absent. CI workflows inject these via
# GitHub Environment Secrets ‚Äî see docs/en/ops/release-secrets.md for the
# server-side rotation matrix.
#
# Value escape rules (Java Properties format, java.util.Properties):
#   - `://` in URLs is SAFE without escape (different from `iosApp/local.xcconfig`,
#     where `//` is a line-comment marker). E.g. `SUPABASE_URL=https://...` works
#     verbatim; do NOT write `https:/$()/` as the xcconfig sibling requires.
#   - `:` and `=` inside VALUES are literal (only meaningful in keys).
#   - `\` must be escaped as `\\` if the value contains a literal backslash.
#   - `#` and `!` are comment markers only when they start a line, so values
#     containing them mid-string are fine.
#   - Leading whitespace on a value is stripped; quote with backslash-space
#     if you need leading whitespace (very rare).
#   - Unicode escapes: `\uXXXX` for non-ASCII characters.
#
# In short: copy-paste your URL / key value verbatim from the dashboard. No
# escaping is needed for any of the values listed below.
#
# What's NOT in this template (intentional):
#   - `sdk.dir` (Android SDK absolute path). Android Studio auto-writes this
#     entry to `local.properties` on first project open with the developer-
#     specific path (e.g. `/Users/<you>/Library/Android/sdk` on macOS). If you
#     build via CLI only without ever opening Android Studio, set the
#     `ANDROID_HOME` shell env var instead ‚Äî AGP's resolution order is
#     `sdk.dir` ‚Üí `ANDROID_HOME` ‚Üí `ANDROID_SDK_ROOT` (deprecated) ‚Üí OS
#     defaults, then it errors out clearly if none resolve. The value is
#     machine-specific and changes per developer, so it is deliberately NOT
#     templated here.

# === Required: backend connectivity =========================================
# Empty values cause the app to start in local-only mode ‚Äî sign-in, profile,
# Discovery feed, and every backend-dependent screen will fail. Setting these
# is the only step needed to unblock account creation + basic app usage.

# Supabase project URL ‚Äî from Supabase Dashboard > Project Settings > API.
SUPABASE_URL=

# Supabase Publishable key (`sb_publishable_‚Ä¶` form, post-2025-11-01). Safe
# to embed in client binaries (RLS enforced server-side). The legacy `anon`
# JWT key was deprecated 2025-11-01 ‚Äî do not use it for new builds.
SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=

# === Optional: analytics + crash reporting ===================================
# Empty values disable each SDK. Even with keys configured, init is also
# gated on the user's analytics opt-in toggle in Settings (Phase 39.2).

# Sentry DSN for the Android Sentry project. Get this from:
#   Sentry > Settings > Projects > skeinly-android > Client Keys (DSN).
SENTRY_DSN_ANDROID=

# PostHog Project API Key (phc_‚Ä¶ prefix). Get from:
#   PostHog > Settings > Project > Project API Key.
POSTHOG_API_KEY=

# PostHog host. Default is the public US cloud. Override only if you self-
# host PostHog or use the EU region (https://eu.i.posthog.com).
POSTHOG_HOST=https://us.i.posthog.com

# === Optional: F1 Pro subscription (Phase 41) ================================
# RevenueCat Public Android SDK Key ‚Äî Dashboard > API Keys > Public Android
# SDK Key (starts with `goog_`). See vendor-setup.md A0d-1 + release-secrets
# ¬ß20. Empty key ‚áí RevenueCatConfig.isConfigured = false ‚áí paywall surfaces
# a "subscriptions unavailable in this build" message rather than crashing.
REVENUECAT_API_KEY_ANDROID=

# === Optional: Android Release signing =======================================
# Required ONLY for `make release-aab-local` / Play Store uploads. Debug
# builds (`./gradlew :androidApp:installDebug` / `make android-install`) do
# not need signing ‚Äî they sign with the default Android debug keystore.
#
# Setup: generate the upload keystore via keytool per `docs/en/ops/
# release-secrets.md ¬ß7` (or via Android Studio: Build > Generate Signed
# Bundle / APK > new keystore). `androidApp/build.gradle.kts` resolves
# the keystore path in this order:
#   1. `KEYSTORE_FILE` in local.properties (this file)
#   2. `KEYSTORE_FILE` env var (used by CI release.yml)
#   3. Default: `upload-keystore.jks` at the repository root
#
# Relative paths are resolved against the repo root; absolute paths are
# used verbatim. The file is git-ignored by the .gitignore pattern `*.jks`
# (also `*.keystore` is covered) ‚Äî no need to add a per-file rule.
#
# === Canonical default filename =============================================
# `upload-keystore.jks` is the project default. Rationale:
#   - Skeinly publishes via Google Play App Signing (Play Console manages
#     the actual app signing key server-side; the developer's local key
#     is the *upload key* that proves authorship of every AAB upload).
#   - `docs/en/ops/release-secrets.md ¬ß7` already uses `upload-keystore.jks`
#     in keytool generation commands + SHA-1 verification examples.
#   - Google's official Android Studio docs use `your-upload-keystore.jks`
#     as the placeholder pattern (developer.android.com/studio/publish/
#     app-signing#generate-key).
# Following the runbook with no overrides produces `upload-keystore.jks` at
# the repo root, which the build then picks up zero-config.
#
# CI release builds receive the matching values via GitHub Secrets
# (KEYSTORE_BASE64 / KEYSTORE_PASSWORD / KEY_ALIAS / KEY_PASSWORD) and the
# release.yml workflow decodes to `$RUNNER_TEMP/upload-keystore.jks` then
# exports `KEYSTORE_FILE` ‚Äî so the env-var branch above (#2) fires on CI.

# Override the keystore path if you use a custom filename or location.
# Leave commented out to use the `upload-keystore.jks` default.
# KEYSTORE_FILE=upload-keystore.jks

# KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=
# KEY_ALIAS=
# KEY_PASSWORD=
